  <h1>Governance &amp; Pilot Programme</h1>

  <h2>Governance Framework</h2>

  <p>
    bearerCORE&#8482; is designed for central bank sovereignty. No private entity controls
    the protocol. Each participating central bank retains full authority over its issuance
    parameters, corridor eligibility, and redemption policies. Cross-corridor governance
    decisions &mdash; such as adjusting FX rate oracles or modifying liquidity lock requirements &mdash;
    are made through a structured proposal and voting mechanism requiring supermajority
    approval from affected central banks.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Governance proposals:</strong> Submitted on-chain, timestamped, and immutable</li>
    <li><strong>Voting thresholds:</strong> Configurable per corridor; default 67% supermajority</li>
    <li><strong>Emergency freeze:</strong> Any central bank governor may freeze bundles in their jurisdiction unilaterally</li>
    <li><strong>Full audit trail:</strong> Every CVIB lifecycle event &mdash; minting, delivery, validation, transfer, redemption &mdash; is logged with cryptographic linkage</li>
    <li><strong>Real-Time Corridor Surveillance:</strong> Central Bank Governors maintain a Command Centre view of all 1,431 bilateral corridors, allowing instant adjustments to liquidity pools and risk limits</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="gauge-wrap">
    <div class="gauge-label">Default Corridor Voting Threshold</div>
    <div class="gauge-meta">67% supermajority required for cross-corridor governance decisions &mdash; configurable per corridor by participating central banks</div>
  </div>

  <h2>Pilot Programme</h2>

  <h3>Phase 1 &mdash; Bilateral Corridor Pilot</h3>
  <p>
    Nigeria &#8596; Ghana Corridor: Active reserve-backed issuance for cross-border trade.
    Central bank minting stations installed. Commercial bank validation desks configured.
    Full lifecycle validation completed across the NGN/GHS corridor.
  </p>

  <h3>Phase 2 &mdash; Regional Bloc Expansion</h3>
  <p>
    East African Community bloc (Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Rwanda). Multi-corridor FX
    resolution activated. Commercial bank API integrations across all participating institutions.
    Retail-grade Digital Money Bundles issued for controlled user testing.
  </p>

  <h3>Phase 3 &mdash; AU Network Deployment</h3>
  <p>
    Full 54-corridor activation. Production-grade Digital Money Bundle issuance. Integration
    with existing RTGS and payment switch infrastructure. Legal tender status subject to each
    central bank&#8217;s legislative framework.
  </p>

